The two officials were concerned that a downgrade could cause clients to stop doing business with the Wall Street bank, the lawsuit said.

Silva and Koh are named as defendants in Segarra's lawsuit, as is her former supervisor, Johnathon J. Kim.

Segarra stated in her federal complaint cited by Bloomberg Businessweek that in a meeting, Silva said the Fed 'possessed information about Goldman that could cause Goldman to ‘explode.'

A spokesman for the New York Fed declined to comment on the specifics of the lawsuit but said its personnel decisions ‘are based exclusively on individual job performance and are subject to thorough review.’

‘We categorically reject any suggestions to the contrary,’ spokesman Jack Gutt said.

