Goldman Sachs said it had no knowledge of internal Fed discussions ‘nor the matters raised by Ms. Segarra.’

‘Goldman Sachs has a comprehensive approach to addressing conflicts through firmwide and divisional policies and infrastructure,’ Goldman Sachs spokesman Michael DuVally said.

Segarra, formerly a legal counsel at Societe Generale, Citigroup and Bank of America, was assigned to Goldman's legal and compliance divisions from October 2011 until May 2012, and looked into three controversial transactions related to Solyndra, Capmark and the merger of El Paso and Kinder Morgan.

At that point, Kim, Silva and Koh fired her and had her escorted from the building by security guards after weeks of disputes and pressure to change her examination findings, the lawsuit said.

Segarra's lawyer, Linda Stengle, said in an interview that Goldman's committees and standards represented ‘a paper policy that didn't really have any weight.’

